<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="1094" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[178,1086,994,1221]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1094">
Comparative notes 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing &amp; I" authorityYear="2014" box="[527,743,994,1015]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Echiaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="1094" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discrepans">
<emphasis box="[527,743,994,1015]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1094">Echiaster discrepans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from other Asian representatives of the genus by numerous significant external and sexual characters, particularly much smaller body size, completely different habitus (much smaller and shorter pronotum, different head shape, much larger elytra), different punctation of the forebody and of the abdomen, posteriorly weakly convex posterior margins of the abdominal tergites VII and VIII, different chaetotaxy of the male sternite VII and VIII, and by the different general morphology of the aedeagus. The number and quality of these differences suggest that it probably belongs to a separate lineage.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
